For many years Barry rode an annual roller coaster of lows and highs .
Autumn and winter brought depression , lethargy - plus a craving for sweets that caused her to gain as much as 30 pounds .
Each spring and summer brought almost manic highs .
She had boundless energy that enabled her to go with little sleep for days and effortlessly shed the excess weight she ' d gained .
By her mid - 40s , these seasonal ups and downs began impairing her work as a writer .
Finally , urged on by her husband , Barry sought professional help .
In 1987 she joined an experimental program at the U . S . National Institute of Mental Health ( NIMH ) in Bethesda , Md .
Research psychiatrist Norman Rosenthal , the program 's director , knew just what Barry was going through .
The gloom of winter had clouded his own moods after he moved from sunny South Africa in 1976 .
He also knew he was n't unique .
" Greek and Roman physicians in ancient times recognized a link between dark moods , lethargy and the change of seasons , " says Rosenthal .
By 1981 , Rosenthal and his NIMH colleagues had identified a medical condition they named Seasonal Affective Disorder , or SAD .
Early research into SAD , now recognized as a distinct kind of clinical depression , was widely discussed in the press .
But since then scientists have made numerous discoveries that have advanced the search for remedies .
Rosenthal 's colleague at the time , Dr . Alfred Lewy , found that increased exposure to bright light in humans could suppress their production of a darkness - related hormone called melatonin .
The light needed to induce this change , Lewy established , was about 2000 lux - about four times brighter than ordinary household lighting .
Rosenthal and his colleagues theorized that if bright light could suppress melatonin secretion , then it might have other effects on the brain , including the reversal of symptoms of depression .
While the precise role of melatonin in SAD has not been pinned down , the theory led to an effective treatment .
By the time Dalene Barry entered the program , this treatment had been established .
She sat for two hours each morning in front of a glowing box of fluorescent bulbs that bathed her with 2500 lux .
