Carbohydrate Craving .
Scientists are still unsure why winter depression happens .
But a decade of research has turned up some surprising findings :
Nearly 80 percent of SAD victims are women .
Researchers at NIMH are unsure why .
SAD can affect people at any age , but typically it begins around the age of 20 and becomes less common between 40 and 50 .
SAD is comparatively rare in children and adolescents .
Children who are affected often have parents with SAD , suggesting the depression has a genetic component .
Some SAD patients experience shifts in their body clocks when they 're depressed in winter .
They are " morning people " at one time of the year and become " evening people " at another .
What is the underlying difference between people with SAD and others ?
A clue to the answer can be found in carbohydrate craving , a common SAD symptom .
Carbohydrates alter brain chemistry by increasing the level of a soothing chemical called serotonin , a neurotransmitter that carries signals between brain cells .
SAD sufferers crave carbohydrates , say Dr . Richard and Judith Wurtman , researchers at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology , because they may need serotonin to lift their mood .
This craving , typically at its strongest from late afternoon through evening , can be intense .
" Some of our patients , " says Rosenthal , " call their desire for candy or cookies an addiction . "
It may be that the serotonin system of the brain has problems regulating itself in SAD sufferers during winter .
Some SAD sufferers respond well to the drug Prozac , thought to influence the brain 's serotonin - using system .
Other brain chemicals and hormones probably play a role in winter depression .
Another neurotransmitter , dopamine , for example , may be inadequate in certain premenopausal women who suffer SAD symptoms .
