Once , my husband and I never seemed to stop talking .
Bob and I would chat over morning coffee , call each other during the day and curl up on the sofa after dinner , weaving words into a comforter that kept us close and warm .
Then , eight years into our marriage , Julia was born , and our conversations turned to baby talk : bottles and burps , sniffles and smiles .
Topics we used to discuss endlessly - - movies , people , places , feelings - - never crossed our lips .
" It 's just new - baby chaos , " we reassured ourselves .
" It 'll pass . "
But when we eavesdropped on parents with older children , we got nervous .
They sounded like flight engineers at a domestic Mission Control , relaying data about soccer practice and dentist appointments .
I asked my friends when they last really talked with their husbands , like grownups , about grownup things .
Most could not remember .
Is having children incompatible with having meaningful adult conversations ?
Not necessarily , says family therapist Rodney J . Shapiro , director of family therapy at California Pacific Medical Center in San Francisco .
Often , busy parents simply get out of the habit of staying in close touch .
" Eventually an emotional distance develops , " Shapiro explains , " and it can be hard to close that gap .
Some couples may stop trying , and that 's when they can get in trouble . "
If you feel out of touch with your spouse and want to reopen the lines of communication , consider the following tips :
1 . Reconnect every day .
" Couples need to talk in a way that makes them feel connected , " says St . Louis psychotherapist Doris Helmering .
Even if you 're so tired you 're ready to drop , spend a few minutes sharing the highs - - and lows - - of each other 's day .
Rather than ask a general question that triggers an automatic response , be specific .
Ask how a big meeting went , whether your spouse likes the new personnel manager .
You 'll show you ' ve been paying attention - - and that you care .
2 . Create opportunities to talk .
" Often couples become overefficient , " notes San Francisco psychotherapist Melody Lowman .
" He goes to the grocery store ; she gets the car washed .
They get more done , but they lose out on time together . "
Casual chitchat while peeling potatoes or washing the car can reinforce your sense of closeness .
" Two people can have a great talk over a double sink while she 's putting on makeup and he 's shaving , " Helmering says .
" What they talk about is less important than sharing something . "
That something may be nothing more than a laugh over the morning funny pages , or a quick update on the latest office romance .
For long talks , make appointments with one another , even if that seems too businesslike .
" Many couples want to be spontaneous , but with children and careers , that 's not realistic , " says Lowman .
" Couples have to make a conscious choice to protect some time as too important for anything but talking . "
Once a week is an absolute minimum ; more is better .
If possible , get out of the house , away from kids and other distractions .
Go for a walk or out to dinner so you can focus on each other .
3 . Discuss outside interests .
It 's important every now and then to exclude the subject of kids - - or the items on your " to do " list - - from your conversation .
Instead , zero in on each other 's interests .
Which topics make your spouse 's eyes light up ?
Think back to the times B . C . ( Before Children ) and the things you used to do together .
Talking about activities you both enjoy - - backpacking , cooking classes , dancing - - can energize a relationship .
4 . Avoid putting your spouse on the defensive .
" When women say , ` Let 's talk , ' many men think , ` She wants to talk about my bad behavior , ' " says Helmering .
" They 're afraid of a lecture on what they should or should n't be doing . "
Husbands and wives should both be aware that nothing puts another person on guard like the word " you , " as in " You always . . . . "
Stick with " I " statements and avoid criticism - - stated or subtle - - so your partner will realize he or she has nothing to fear .
When you do have a gripe , also offer a possible solution .
Saying " I feel we 're out of touch " throws the problem to your partner .
If you add , " I think we should sit down every night and have a cup of tea together after the kids are in bed , " you ' ve offered a practical suggestion .
Ann McGinn began sneaking cigarettes from her mother when she was 12 .
By age 18 she was smoking a pack a day and boasted of having taught her older sister to smoke .
By the time she reached her 20s , her daily fix had doubled .
" Most mornings I ' d light a cigarette within minutes of waking up , " says McGinn , a secretary in Quincy , Mass .
" I planned my life around smoking . "
While relishing the warm rush of smoke sucked into her lungs , she overlooked the hacking cough and chronic bronchitis she developed .
But at age 40 , she could no longer ignore her body 's distress calls .
" I thought , I want a better life , " McGinn says .
She decided she needed to quit .
While more than 44 million Americans had sworn off cigarettes by 1990 , the percentage of women quitting was slightly lower than that of men .
And each day about 1500 young women light up for the first time , joining 22.2 million other female smokers in the this country .
If trends continue , female smokers in the United States will outnumber their male counterparts ( 24 million ) by the end of the decade .
" For many years , lung cancer was considered a man 's disease , but now it is the leading cause of cancer death among American women , " said U . S . Surgeon General Antonia C . Novello in a 1990 speech .
Although smoking - related deaths among men are declining , it is expected that the rates for women will keep rising into the next century .
And in some ways smoking is actually harsher on women than on men .
Women who smoke are at risk for all of the same smoking - related diseases as men , plus ones related to the female reproductive system and pregnancy .
To make matters worse , women tend to develop a type of lung cancer called adenocarcinoma .
This malignancy grows faster and spreads to distant organs more often than squamous - cell carcinoma , which men are more apt to get .
Female smokers may also develop chronic obstructive pulmonary diseases ( COPD ) - - including asthma , emphysema and bronchitis - - earlier than men do .
" Men usually develop emphysema in their 60s and 70s , " says Dr . Alfred Munzer , president of the American Lung Association .
" But I ' m seeing more women in their late 40s and early 50s with totally disabling emphysema . "
What accounts for this disparity ?
Because women 's respiratory passages are smaller than men 's , they seem to be more sensitive to tobacco , says Dr . James Kiley , chief of airway diseases at the U . S . National Heart , Lung and Blood Institute in Bethesda , Md .
Women who smoke expose themselves to a variety of other health risks , including cardiovascular disease .
Smoking as few as one to four cigarettes a day may increase a woman 's risk of heart attack by two to three times .
The habit can also lead to stroke and cancers of the oral cavity , pharynx , larynx , esophagus , kidney and bladder .
And it contributes to cataracts and to cancers of the pancreas and cervix .
Female smokers may experience irregular menstrual cycles , take longer to conceive and have a greater risk of ectopic pregnancy , according to the 1990 U . S . Surgeon General 's report .
Women who smoke during pregnancy are more likely to experience bleeding , premature rupture of the membranes , spontaneous abortion and preterm delivery .
Evidence also suggests that cigarette smoking , which causes an estrogen deficiency in women , increases the risk of osteoporosis and early menopause .
Postmenopausal women who smoke and take estrogen - replacement therapy may lose its protective effect , according to a study by Dr . Douglas Kiel , assistant professor of medicine at Harvard Medical School .
" Women who took estrogen and were smokers had the same risk of hip fracture as those who did n't take estrogen , " he says .
Even if a woman has smoked for years , quitting can have a powerfully positive effect on her long - term health .
Within ten years of quitting , the risk of lung cancer falls to 30 to 50 percent that of smokers .
After 15 years of abstinence , the risk of heart disease is comparable to that of women who have never smoked .
In smokers without COPD , stopping smoking improves pulmonary function within the first few months .
In just the first few years of cessation , the risk of cervical cancer drops substantially .
Quitting , however , is difficult .
" Women often use cigarettes to handle all their negative emotions , like stress , depression , loneliness and anger , " says epidemiologist Peggy O ' Hara , an epidemiologist at the University of Miami School of Medicine in Florida .
Some studies suggest women who stop smoking may have more intense cravings for cigarettes than do men who quit , says Dr . Susan Fiester , medical director of the Psychiatric Institute in Washington , D . C .
This may be because there 's a biological difference in the way men and women respond to nicotine .
Research conducted by Cynthia Pomerleau of the University of Michigan found that even when women smoke fewer cigarettes than men , they achieve comparable blood nicotine levels .
This suggests , says Pomerleau , " that the effects of a given dose of nicotine may be more pronounced in women than in men . "
One of the greatest deterrents to giving up cigarettes is the fear of gaining weight , a concern women consistently report more than men .
One reason is that women seem to have a different pattern of weight gain , according to preliminary evidence from the Lung Health Study sponsored by the U . S . National Heart , Lung and Blood Institute .
" It appears that men gain the most within the first three months after quitting , and then stabilize , " says O ' Hara .
" Women continue to show gains over the first year . "
Still , the average woman who quits will gain only five to eight pounds .
According to a 1990 report in the Journal of the American Medical Association , smokers who quit cold turkey have success rates approaching 50 percent and are more likely to remain abstinent than those who try tapering off .
" Cold turkey hurts the most , for the least amount of time , " says Doug Coleman , a trainer for the American Cancer Society 's Fresh Start smoking - cessation program .
