Eight - year - old William awoke early that Christmas morning , eager to see what was under our tree .
When he found the skis , he looked faintly disappointed .
Skis had not been high on his wish list , but I knew my son would need them for an upcoming family trip .
" Thanks , " he said softly .
As it turned out , the skis were the best gift he ever received .
William took to the sport his first day on the slopes .
Soon an instructor persuaded him to join the resort 's junior race program .
For the next ten years , William skied every winter weekend .
Those first skis were soon replaced , but they had already bestowed benefits far more lasting than the model train , bicycle and record player that succeeded them .
The skis taught William self - discipline and persistence .
Each winter weekend morning , sometimes in subzero cold , the budding racer had to pull himself from bed to be on the mountain by 8 a . m .
When he fell , he got up and tried again .
At home , he learned to budget his time to allow for homework and workouts .
As a racer , William never rose to Olympic caliber .
But today he is a hard - working , focused 23 - year - old , willing to dare because he is not afraid to fail .
I sometimes wonder how different he might be if he ' d received some other gift that Christmas .
This holiday season , we We all hope to give gifts whose value will outlive the gifts themselves .
Sometimes we anticipate their lasting value . Sometimes the " value added " is an unplanned extra .
When parents pick gifts for their children , of course , the challenge - - and the rewards - - are the greatest of all .
We want to give gifts that will broaden and brighten a child 's world and be remembered for years to come .
" A gift is not merely something material , " declares child development expert Barbara Nordhaus of the Yale Child Study Center .
" It 's an expression of love and caring .
Giving your children specially chosen gifts is part of the parents ' role of nurturing and stimulating . "
How can you choose gifts that will benefit your child over the years ?
Keep these guidelines in mind :
Start out simple .
Gifts do n't have to be expensive or elaborate to have enduring value .
When I was eight , I found a pocket flashlight in my Christmas stocking .
It was the simplest of gifts - - a " stocking stuffer . "
But I was delighted .
The flashlight allowed me to read under the blankets at night without my parents knowing .
That started a habit of nighttime reading that continues .
For novelist Joyce Carol Oates , her most memorable gifts were the most humble ones .
Growing up near Buffalo , N . Y . , in an area where winters can be bitter , Oates received " hand - sewn and knitted things - - dresses , mitten - and - cap sets , sweaters of the softest angora wool .
What effort must have gone into these gifts ! "
Equally memorable - - and simple - - was her first book , Alice 's Adventures in Wonderland and Through the Looking Glass ,
" a gift from my grandmother , which I prize to this day , " she says .
Match the child 's interests .
Fathers give their sons footballs , mothers give their daughters dolls , because that 's what they enjoyed as children .
But Johnny is n't Dad , and Mary is n't Mom .
" Gifts should n't be given to carry out a parent 's agenda , " Nordhaus says .
" They should be picked for the child , not the parent .
Kids tell you who they are , verbally and nonverbally . "
An attentive parent can gauge what a child likes and choose a gift accordingly .
If your child asks for something specific , consider it carefully .
When five - year - old Mark Huggins insisted he wanted a violin for Christmas , his mother dismissed his request as a youngster 's whim .
Mark persisted , and Ellie Huggins finally gave in .
Today , 30 years later , Mark is associate concertmaster of the Pittsburgh Symphony a symphony orchestra .
Challenge your child .
Often the best gifts are those that children grow into , not out of .
" Honey , we 're dead , " Linda moaned , as the van plunged down a steep hill and rolled over .
Linda , who had neglected to wear her seat belt , was tossed from the driver 's seat like a rag doll .
Her body slammed into the console between the front seats , and she felt a crushing pain in her lower abdomen .
Then her head rammed and shattered the windshield .
She was knocked cold .
Linda awoke to a quiet , strange world .
The van had come to rest on its right side .
She was sitting on the passenger window with Honey , wide - eyed , on her lap .
To her left lay the dislodged passenger seat and , jammed between it and the now - vertical floor , her electric wheelchair .
The headlights shone dimly , illuminating a thickly wooded area .
The clock on the dashboard read 2 : 20 .
The sliding panel door had partly opened , and the icy night breeze made Linda shiver .
Aside from her windbreaker , she wore only a T - shirt and thin leggings .
She felt as though she had been pummeled with a baseball bat .
Reflexively , she touched her side to check the stabbing pain in her ribs .
Something 's broken , she thought , wincing .
Bits of glass clung to her hair and formed a shimmering sea around her .
Where are we ?
Slowly , she remembered going off the road just past Exit 10 southeast of Hartford .
She could hear an occasional car but had no idea how far she was from the highway .
She thought back to the menacing flatbed .
The driver must have known he hit me .
He has to stop , or at least get the police !
But , as time wore on , Linda heard only low music from the radio , a soft chorus of chirping crickets and the sound of water running close by .
Then she remembered the telephone .
She found it lodged under the gas and brake pedals above her head .
Using her left hand to brace her feeble right arm , she got hold of the phone and dialed 911 .
Busy .
That 's strange , she thought .
Linda had worked as a police dispatcher and knew emergency lines should never be busy .
She dialed Don 's number .
Also busy .
Without realizing it , Linda had driven beyond range of any of the antennas that make car phones work .
But she had another recourse .
Don had installed a CB radio in her van .
She flipped it on .
The radio was tuned to 19 , the channel frequently used by truckers , but all Linda could hear was a static - filled jumble of voices .
" Breaker one - nine .
I ' m on a ten - thirty - three , " she said , giving the code for emergencies .
No one seemed to hear her .
" Breaker one - nine , breaker , breaker ! "
Still no answer .
The van 's headlights faded , and the CB went silent .
The battery was dead . The radio and telephone were without power .
Linda felt a wave of despair , but steeled herself to resist it .
She had always been a survivor .
Doctors had predicted she would n't live past 16 .
Now she was well beyond that , and had always made sure her life was full of activity , friends and hope .
When daylight comes , someone will see us , she thought .
She willed her body to leave its uncomfortable place on the window but found herself too weak to move even an inch .
